    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bell's Theorem is actually a bit like a detective story where the detective (Einstein) thought there was a secret note hidden in the evidence box (hidden variables), but the new evidence (Bell's inequalities) proved that note doesn't exist. It's not just that we can't see the mechanism yet; it's that the mechanism *doesn't exist* in the way we imagined.\n\nThink of it like this: if you have two perfectly synchronized dice, Einstein thought there must be a tiny, invisible string connecting them that tells them what to roll. Bell's Theorem proved that no matter how complex that string is, it can't explain the results unless it's faster than light. So, there is no \"under the hood\" secret script that pre-determines the outcome based on local conditions.\n\nInstead, the universe seems to operate on a level where the properties of the particles don't exist until they are measured, and the \"choice\" is made instantaneously across space. It's like the dice aren't rolling at all until you look, and the moment you look at one, the other one magically decides its number to match, without any signal traveling between them.\n\nThis is why physicists are so fascinated by it",
